<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" id="teilangusage" lang="en">
   <head>Using tei:langUsage</head>
   <p>using tei:langUsage </p>
   <p>to be added</p><p>The <tag>langUsage</tag> element in the <tag>teiHeader</tag> contains a list of declared ancient and modern languages, each of which has the form:</p>
<list><item><tag>language id="la"</tag>Latin<tag>/language</tag></item><item><tag>language id="grc"</tag>Ancient Greek<tag>/language</tag></item><item><tag>language id="en"</tag>English<tag>/language</tag></item><item><tag>language id="el"</tag>Modern Greek<tag>/language</tag></item></list><p>The <att>id</att> of each <tag>language</tag> should contain the 2-letter ISO language code, where one is available, or the 3-digit code where one is not (as in the case of ancient Greek).</p><p>These languages are then available to be referred to by the <att>lang</att> or <att>xml:lang</att> attribute on any element in the file. See <tag>tei:foreign</tag> and <xref href="languages.xml">languages.xml</xref>.</p></div>
